1. Create a User with Non-Interactive Shell
sudo useradd -s /sbin/nologin <username>

Verify:
grep deployuser /etc/passwd
You’ll see something like:
<username>:x:1003:1003::/home/<username>:/sbin/nologin
✅ This means the user exists but cannot log in via SSH or terminal.

2. Create a User with Expiry Date

sudo useradd -e YYYY-MM-DD <username>

verify:
sudo chage -l testuser

3. Combine Both Options

You can also create a non-interactive user with an expiry date together:

sudo useradd -s /sbin/nologin -e 2025-12-31 tempdeploy

Verify:
grep tempdeploy /etc/passwd
sudo chage -l tempdeploy

4. Create a Regular User
sudo useradd <username>
Example:
sudo useradd devopsuser
sudo passwd devopsuser

5. Add User to a Specific Group
sudo usermod -aG docker <user name>

6. Add User to the Sudoers List (Root Permission)
Add to wheel group (Recommended for CentOS/RHEL)

sudo usermod -aG wheel devopsadmin

Verify that the wheel group has sudo privileges:
sudo grep wheel /etc/sudoers

7. Add User Directly in Sudoers File

Edit sudoers safely using visudo:
sudo visudo
Add this line at the end:
devopsadmin  ALL=(ALL)  NOPASSWD:ALL
or (if you want password prompt):
devopsadmin  ALL=(ALL)  ALL
Save and exit (Esc, then :wq).
✅ The user now has full root permissions.

8. Create a File in /etc/sudoers.d/ (Best Practice for Automation)
Create a new sudoers file:

echo "devopsadmin ALL=(ALL) NOPASSWD:ALL" | sudo tee /etc/sudoers.d/devopsadmin

Set correct permissions:
sudo chmod 440 /etc/sudoers.d/devopsadmin
